<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06116181 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06116181 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; QUAKE CLEANUP -- Red Cross and city workerssalvage valuables from the ruins of the International Motel in Puerto Limon,Costa Rica, on Tuesday.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  COSTA-RICA; ROAD; REPAIR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Costa Rica on Wednesday began repairing crumbled highways and bridges ruinedby a killer earthquake so it can resume exporting crops vital to its economy.;   The earthquake Monday registered 7.4 on the Richter scale and claimed 53dead in Costa Rica and 24 in Panama. Hundreds were injured, and thousands morelost their homes.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  COSTA RICA BEGINS REPAIRING ROADS TO RESUMEEXPORTS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     U.S. and Nicaraguan helicopters Wednesday flew into remote areas of CostaRica's hard-hit Atlantic coast and other areas near the Panamanian bordersearching for additional victims and assessing emergency relief needs.;    TheWorld Bank authorized $80 million in loans for road repairs, but Costa RicanPresident Rafael Angel Calderon said at least $170 million would be needed todo the job.;    The highway connecting the Caribbean city of Puerto Limon andSan Jose 75 miles to the west suffered some of the worst damage. Limon is animportant port for shipping bananas and coffee, Costa Rica's main exports.Together they bring in about $500 million a year.;    &quot;Our main worry now isthat thousands of boxes of bananas ready for export will be lost because wecan't get them out,&quot; said Antonio Cruz, an official of the Standard Fruit Co.installation near Limon.;    The quake buckled parts of the 55-mile coastalroad from Limon south to Sixaola. It split the highway with fissures up toeight feet deep and three feet across. Rails of the railroad used to move thebanana harvest were bent like pipe cleaners in S-shapes at several points.;   Meanwhile, hundreds of Sixaola's residents have built lean-tos and tents withblankets and plastic sheets. Some simply sleep outside on the ground for feartheir houses will collapse in another of the tremors that cut power andtelephone service to the town.;    About 600 houses were destroyed or damagedin and around Sixaola, said Maj. Gerardo Salazar, the regional National Guardcommander.;    Calderon said that the first $20 million from the World Bankwould be available next week and that the Inter-American Development Bank haddonated $200,000 more.;    Limon, a city of 130,000 residents, suffered theworst damage from the earthquake because it was closest to the epicenter. Butthere also was destruction in Panama.;    Helicopters from the U.S. SouthernCommand, based in Panama, flew over the affected areas to assess the damage,and Panamanian planes were flying some food and medicine to the area.;    AU.S. officer said the United States had not sent medical help but expectedPanama to request it.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Jose, Costa Rica  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910425  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  441  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday April 25, 199100116181,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>